            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Robert Miller is a ghost of a San Francisco that is rapidly fading. Born and raised in the foggy avenues of the Outer Sunset, his life has been shaped by the city's working-class rhythms, not its tech-fueled gold rushes. His father was a Muni driver and his mother a waitress, their lives a testament to union wages and the quiet stability of a two-bedroom, rent-controlled apartment. Robert, never one for academics, scraped by with a general studies diploma from his local high school, feeling adrift in a city that was just beginning to feel too big for him.\n\nFor a decade after graduation, he drifted through a series of jobs\u2014deli counter clerk, warehouse stocker, bike messenger\u2014none of which offered more than a paycheck. The turning point came in his late twenties when his mother was diagnosed with early-onset Alzheimer's. Robert became her primary caregiver. In the difficult, tender moments of helping her navigate her declining world, he discovered an unexpected well of patience and a calling for care. It was the first thing that had ever felt truly meaningful.\n\nAfter his mother passed, he used his small inheritance to get his Certified Nursing Assistant (CNA) license. He found his niche not in a frantic hospital but in the relative calm of a public high school health office. For twenty years, he\u2019s been the steady presence who dispenses ice packs, bandages, and quiet reassurance to teenagers navigating everything from sports injuries to panic attacks. His $58,000 salary is a constant squeeze, but his rent-controlled apartment, now his alone, makes it possible.\n\nHis daily routine is a familiar loop: the N-Judah train for his 2.5-mile commute, the predictable chaos of the school day, and the quiet evenings spent with a book or watching the Giants game. He is single, with a few lifelong friends he meets for beers at a neighborhood dive bar. Robert feels like a relic, watching the city of his youth transform into a playground for the wealthy. He doesn't dream of wealth, but of a quiet retirement where he can afford to stay in the city that holds his entire history. His greatest hope is simple: to remain, a quiet anchor in the ever-shifting tides of San Francisco."
        },
