            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. He remembers the heavy, comforting rumble of the Muni bus felt through the soles of his Keds. His father was driving, and Robert, about eight years old, sat on the worn bench seat right behind him. The air smelled of diesel, damp fog, and his dad\u2019s Old Spice. As they passed the diner where his mother worked, his father would give a quick, sharp toot of the horn. That sound\u2014a private signal in the public din\u2014made the entire, sprawling city feel like their own. It taught him dignity wasn\u2019t loud. (Age 8)\n\n2. His legs burned as he pedaled his messenger bike up the impossibly steep California Street hill, a tube of architectural plans strapped to his back. He delivered it to a silent, glass-walled office where young people in expensive clothes typed on glowing screens. He was a ghost, a sweaty delivery system. He wasn't envious of their money, but he felt the profound chasm between his world and theirs. That day, he understood he wasn't just adrift; he was becoming invisible in his own hometown. (Age 22)\n\n3. His mother stared at the butter knife, her hand trembling slightly. \"Who are you?\" she asked, her eyes lost in a fog only she could see. Robert\u2019s chest seized, but he gently placed his hand over hers, guiding it to the warm toast. \"I'm Robert,\" he said softly. For a single, lucid moment, her eyes cleared. \"My Robert.\" The wave of heartbreak was met by an even stronger surge of purpose. In that Sunset district kitchen, he found the first work that ever truly mattered. (Age 28)\n\n4. A lanky freshman stumbled into the health office, not bleeding, but hyperventilating before a math final. Robert didn't say much. He got the boy a glass of water and sat with him, talking quietly about a recent Giants game until his breathing slowed. The boy left with a quiet \"thanks,\" his panic replaced by a fragile calm. In that moment, Robert knew he\u2019d found his place. He wasn't just dispensing bandages; he was a small, steady anchor in the chaotic sea of adolescence. (Age 32)\n\n5. On his evening commute, the N-Judah slowed past the corner where the old dive bar his buddies used to frequent once stood. Now, it was a sleek, cold-pressed juice bar with a neon sign. He felt a familiar, quiet ache\u2014not of anger, but of mourning. He was a walking archive of a city that no longer existed, a keeper of memories for places that had been erased. His greatest ambition wasn't to succeed in the new San Francisco, but to simply outlast it. (Age 51)"
